arch:property.oc:show_val: Short period of sedimentation following abandonment.

Locus 84 is the layer of sedimentation above the stairway and below the collapse of the “hypocaust room.” This locus was a fine silt with Munsell 7.5 YR 5/4 (brown). It had few substantial inclusions, with only small samples of pottery, bone, metal, shell, and glass. There were a number of marble tiles, but generally this locus was quite different from the collapse above it, lacking the major architectural fragments. This locus is also different from the dumping loci in the rest of the “hypocaust room,” without any hypocaust or flue tiles, and without the inclusions of ash and plaster. This locus is therefore seen as part of the sedimentation of the “hypocaust room,” and is therefore assigned to Stage 5.

Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
Soil below the collapse (Locus 3) above the steps in the “hypocaust room”
